<span class="displaytext"><b> </b><p>today, in pennsylvania, (candidate full) outlined a comprehensive pro-growth strategy that includes several new initiatives. included in this plan are several new initiatives to help americans confront economic challenges while focusing government on actually helping families. <b><u> </u></b></p><p>the new initiatives:  </p><p>gas prices: (candidate full) believes we should institute a summer gas tax holiday. hard-working american families are suffering from higher gasoline prices. (candidate full) calls on congress to suspend the 18.4 cent federal gas tax and 24.4 cent diesel tax from memorial day to labor day. <b> </b></p><p>student loans: (candidate full) is proposing a student loan continuity plan. students face the possibility that the credit crunch will disrupt loans for the fall semester. (candidate full) calls on the federal government and the 50 governors to anticipate problems and expand the lender-of-last resort capabilities for each state's guarantee agency. <b> </b></p><p>middle class tax cuts: (candidate full) will double the personal exemption for dependents. (candidate full) believes the tax code should be less of a burden on those, whether they are mothers and fathers or single parents, who are trying to raise a family. he proposes to raise the personal exemption for each dependent from $3,500 to $7,000. <b> </b></p><p>a simpler tax code: (candidate full) will propose an alternative new and simpler tax system -- and give america a real choice. when this reform is enacted, all who wish to stay under the current system could still do so, but everyone else could choose a vastly less complicated system with two tax rates and a generous standard deduction. americans do not resent paying their rightful share of taxes -- what they do resent is being subjected to thousands of pages of needless and often irrational rules and demands from the irs. <b> </b></p><p>government spending: (candidate full) proposes a one-year spending pause to evaluate programs. he believes that outside of essential military and veterans programs there should be a one-year discretionary spending pause that should be used for a top-to-bottom review of the effectiveness of federal programs. <b> </b></p><p>medicare growth: (candidate full) believes that we should not subsidize the prescription drugs of america's most affluent individuals. he will propose reforms to reduce the large subsidies in the medicare drug program.</p></span>



